   \begin{frame}{What is discrete mathematics?}
        \item Discrete mathematics is the study of mathematical structures that are
fundamentally discrete rather than continuous. In contrast to real numbers that have the property of varying ”smoothly”, the objects studied
in discrete mathematics such as integers, graphs, and statements in
logic do not vary smoothly in this way, but have distinct, separated
values.\\
    \end{frame}
    
      \begin{frame}{Logic and Proofs}
            \begin{center}
      \begin{tabular}{ |c|c|c| } 
      \hline
     \textbf{ propositional logic} & \textbf{first order logic} \\
      \hline
      true or false & true or false \\ 
      \hline
       Ex: 17 is greater than 12. & x is greater than y. \\ 
      \hline
      \end{tabular}
        \end{center}
        \paragraph{"17 is greater than 12." its a universal truth\\
        but "x is greater than y." is not the universal truth
        }
    \end{frame}
    
    \begin{frame}{ Probability}
        \item it is the study of random processes and their outcomes.\\
        
        
        \paragraph{Steps to find the probability\\
Step 1 − Calculate all possible outcomes of the experiment.\\
Step 2 − Calculate the number of favorable outcomes of the experiment.\\
Step 3 − Apply the corresponding probability formula.\\}

        {\textit{Probabilityofoccurenceofanevent =}$$\frac{Totalnumberoffavourableoutcome}{TotalnumberofOutcomes}$$}
    \end{frame}
    
    \begin{frame}
    {\large Example:\\}
        Tossing a Coin
If a coin is tossed, there are two possible outcomes − Heads (H) or Tails (T)
So, Total number of outcomes = 2

Hence, the probability of getting a Head (H) on top is 1/2 and the probability of getting a Tails (T) on top is 1/2\\
    
        \begin{center}
		\begin{figure}[h]
		\begin{center}
			\centering							\includegraphics[width=8cm,height=5cm]{headtail.jpg}
			\end{center}
			\caption{{\huge \textbf{coin}}}
		\end{figure}
	\end{center}
\end{frame}
    
    
    \begin{frame}{Graph Theory}
        \paragraph{ A graph (denoted as G=(V,E)) consists of a non-empty set of vertices or nodes V and a set of edges E.}
        
         \begin{center}
		\begin{figure}[h]
		\begin{center}
			\centering							\includegraphics[width=8cm,height=4cm]{graph2.png}
			\end{center}
			\caption{{graph}}
		\end{figure}
	\end{center}
	\paragraph{The two discrete structures that we will cover are graphs and trees. A graph is a set of points, called nodes or vertices, which are interconnected by a set of lines called edges. The study of graphs, or graph theory is an important part of a number of disciplines in the fields of mathematics, engineering and computer science.}
	
    \end{frame}
    
    \begin{frame}{Example}
        \paragraph{Graphs are nothing but connected nodes(vertex). So any network related, routing, finding relation, path etc related real life applications use graphs.\\GPS/Google Maps/Yahoo Maps, to find a route based on shortest route all are based on graph theory }
        
        \begin{center}
		\begin{figure}[h]
		\begin{center}
			\centering							\includegraphics[width=8cm,height=4cm]{graph1.png}
			\end{center}
			\caption{{graph}}
		\end{figure}
	\end{center}
        
    \end{frame}
    
